        'Once you\'ve audited your practice and identified the representativeness gap, the design work begins.',
        'There are a handful of principles that should guide how you redesign your practice for transfer. These are not rules to follow mechanically. They\'re orientations that should inform every design decision you make.',
        'Principle one: keep the information, change the difficulty. The most common mistake in making practice more manageable is to remove informational complexity. Don\'t. Instead, change the difficulty by changing the task demands, the time constraints, the success criteria, the stakes — but keep the real cues present. A beginner version of a complex performance should still contain the key perceptual demands of the expert version, even if the task is simpler. The point of a modified game is not to make the game easier. It\'s to focus the performer on a specific perceptual demand within the real game.',
