        'Principle three: require decisions, not executions. Real performance is a continuous stream of decision-making. If your practice can be completed successfully without making real decisions — without genuine uncertainty about what to do next, driven by what you\'re reading in the environment — it is an execution drill, not a skill development activity. Execution drills have their place. They are not sufficient. Build practice activities where the performer regularly faces genuine choice points, and where the quality of the choice depends on the quality of what they\'re reading.',
        'Principle four: introduce consequential ambiguity. Real information environments are ambiguous. The cues are not perfectly clear. The signal is embedded in noise. The decision windows are short. Practice that presents clean, unambiguous versions of the cues you need to read is not training your perceptual system to handle the real thing. Introduce ambiguity. Create situations where the right reading isn\'t obvious. Make the noise real. Your perceptual system needs to learn to parse the actual signal — not a cleaned-up version of it.',
        'Principle five: let the environment give feedback, not the coach. When feedback comes from a coach telling you what you did wrong, you learn to read the coach. When feedback comes from the environment telling you whether your reading was accurate — the ball went where you expected, the client responded the way you predicted, the negotiation moved in the direction you read — you learn to read the environment. The second type of feedback is what builds perceptual skill. Design for it.',
        'Principle six: variable difficulty at fixed representativeness. You can adjust how hard the task is. You cannot adjust away the informational structure. The perceptual demands of performance are the floor of every practice activity you design. Difficulty can be raised or lowered above that floor. The floor itself does not move.',
        'These six principles are not a formula. They\'re a way of thinking about design decisions. Every time you design a practice activity, run it through these orientations. Where does it break down? Where does it fail to be representative? Fix those things and you\'re moving in the right direction.',
