        'The honest practitioners — the ones who actually close this gap — do two things. First, they run the audit. They get specific about what performance actually demands from them perceptually, and they get honest about whether their current practice requires those perceptual demands. They find the gap. They don\'t rationalize it or minimize it. They see it.',
        'Second, they redesign. They don\'t just add representative practice on top of their existing routine. They rebuild the routine around representativeness as a non-negotiable criterion. Every practice activity earns its place by requiring them to read real cues. Anything that doesn\'t get redesigned or removed.',
